1. RESOLVED — Restock modal line-item text no longer overlaps; long item names and dense PO/request metadata now use available space first and word-wrap when needed.

Implementation details:
- Updated restock workflow modal containers to use a viewport-height cap with internal scrolling (`max-h-[90vh]` and `overflow-y-auto`) so content can expand without being forced into cramped, overlapping rows.
- Reworked request item rows and selected purchase order item rows from fixed equal-width grids to min/max grids that allocate more room to product names first, then wrap quantity, unit-cost, received, and total text as needed.
- Added `min-w-0` and `break-words` to modal rows and metadata blocks so long product names, PO numbers, supplier names, user names, and currency/date text wrap inside their cells instead of overflowing into neighboring columns.
- Adjusted supplier request and PO list modal text blocks to be flexible (`min-w-0 flex-1`) so action buttons retain their space while descriptive text wraps cleanly.
- The same line-item layout improvements were applied while adding hold controls, so the extra `Hold item` action does not create another overlap point.

How to verify this issue was truthfully resolved:
1. Start the admin app and open `/admin/restock`.
2. Create or locate restock requests and POs that include very long product names, supplier names, PO numbers, and/or notes.
3. Open these restock workflow modals:
   - Supplier current requests modal.
   - Individual request detail modal.
   - Supplier purchase orders modal.
   - Individual purchase order detail modal.
   - Generate PO modal.
   - Edit PO modal.
   - Receive PO modal.
   - Release from hold modal.
4. Resize the browser to desktop, tablet, and narrow/mobile widths. Verify long text uses available horizontal space, then wraps onto additional lines without overlapping adjacent quantity/cost/total/action columns.
5. Confirm modal bodies scroll vertically when content exceeds the viewport instead of compressing rows until text overlaps.
6. Run `npx tsc --noEmit` and verify TypeScript passes.
7. Run `npm run lint` and verify lint passes.
